Subject: Retrieving data from the handyboard

Hi team,

I'm working on a fun project involving an old handyboard and trying to visualize some data it generates.  It seems like the data is sent out through a COM port in a specific format.  

I'm hoping someone might have a program or some code snippets that can help me interpret these signals. I'm using an old Win98 PC and Visual Studio 6.0 for this project.

Here's a snippet of the function I'm using to process the data:

```c++
int map[15][15][5]; 
void output() 	{ 		
    int v=0; 		
    int h=0; 		
    int o=0; 		
    for(v = 0; v<15; v++) { 			
        for(h=0; h<15; h++) { 				
            for(o=0; o<5; o++){ 		                      
                serial_putchar(map[v][h][o]); 				
            } 			
        } 		
    } 	
}

Subject: Re: Type conversion.

Email body:

Hi there!

I saw your question about converting integers to floating point numbers and thought I'd share a helpful example from a project I'm working on.  It involves controlling a buzzer with a knob, and the code needs to make sure the frequency is set correctly.

Here's the snippet:

```c
/*     adjusts the frequency of the buzzer with the knob */
void main() {
 float h=0.0;
 while(1){
  printf("Press start to  adjust pitch...\\n");
  start_press();
  printf("Stop to quit\\n");
  while(1) {
   h=(20.0*(float) knob());   <--see here
   if (h<20.0){
    h=20.0;
   }
   set_beeper_pitch(h);
   beeper_on();
   if (stop_button()) {
    beep();
    break;
   }
  }
 }
}
```

Let me know if you have any other questions about programming!

Best,

Duncan

